{"title_page": "James Scott of Balwearie", "text_new": "'''James Scott of Balwearie''' (died 1606) was a Scottish landowner and supporter of the rebel earls.\n\nHe was the son of Walter Scott of Balwearie and Janet Lindsay, a daughter of John Lindsay of Dowhill. His mother had been married to Andrew Lundie, and later married George Douglas, a son of Sir Robert Douglas of [[Lochleven Castle|Lochleven Castle]] and [[Margaret Erskine]].\n\nHis grandfather, also [[William Scott, Lord Balwearie|William Scott of Balwearie]], was a [[Lord of Session]]. His step-father, George Douglas, had helped [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] escape from [[Lochleven Castle]] in 1568.\n\nScott was agent of the rebel Catholic lords in 1594. It was rumoured he was involved in a plot to depose [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] in favour of his infant son [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. Balwearie was captured on 11 January by the [[Provost of Edinburgh]], [[Alexander Home of North Berwick]] and imprisoned in [[Edinburgh Castle]].<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 499, 510.</ref> On 28 January 1595 interrogated and described a meeting in August 1594 at an ostler's house next to the Kirk of [[Menmuir]] with the Earls of [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell|Bothwell]], [[William Douglas, 10th Earl of Angus|Angus]], [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly|Huntly]], [[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll|Erroll]], [[George Sinclair, 5th Earl of Caithness|Caithness]] and others. These nobles subscribed to a band, a treasonous league, to defend themselves against the king, [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]]. At a second meeting in Angus a plan to capture James VI at [[Stirling Castle]] was discussed. Following their victory at the [[battle of Glenlivet]], the Earl of Huntly sent a messenger to Flanders and the Pope to report their \"happy success\".<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 522-3.</ref>\n\n[[Walter Scott, 1st Lord Scott of Buccleuch|Walter Scott of Buccleuch]] asked [[Anne of Denmark]] to intercede for his life and he was imprisoned and fined.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 524-5, 526.</ref>\n\nHe died in 1606.\n\n==Family==\nJames Scott married Elizabeth Wardlaw, daughter of Andrew Wardlaw of Torrie. Their children included:\n* Barbara Scott, who married David Graham of Fintry.\n* Janet Scott, who married John Boswell of Balmuto.\n* James Scott of Logie, who married Katherine Creick.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, James}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:1606 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''James Scott of Balwearie''' (died 1606) was a Scottish landowner and supporter of the rebel earls.\n\nHe was the son of Walter Scott of Balwearie and Janet Lindsay, a daughter of John Lindsay of Dowhill. His mother had been married to Andrew Lundie, and later married George Douglas, a son of Sir Robert Douglas of [[Lochleven Castle|Lochleven Castle]] and [[Margaret Erskine]].\n\nHis grandfather, also [[William Scott, Lord Balwearie|William Scott of Balwearie]], was a [[Lord of Session]]. His step-father, George Douglas, had helped [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] escape from [[Lochleven Castle]] in 1568.\n\nScott was agent of the rebel Catholic lords in 1594. It was rumoured he was involved in a plot to depose [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] in favour of his infant son [[Prince Henry|Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. Balwearie was captured on 11 January by the [[Provost of Edinburgh]], [[Alexander Home of North Berwick]] and imprisoned in [[Edinburgh Castle]].<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 499, 510.</ref> On 28 January 1595 interrogated and described a meeting in August 1594 at an ostler's house next to the Kirk of [[Menmuir]] with the Earls of [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell|Bothwell]], [[William Douglas, 10th Earl of Angus|Angus]], [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly|Huntly]], [[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll|Erroll]], [[George Sinclair, 5th Earl of Caithness|Caithness]] and others. These nobles subscribed to a band, a treasonous league, to defend themselves against the king, [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]]. At a second meeting in Angus a plan to capture James VI at [[Stirling Castle]] was discussed. Following their victory at the [[battle of Glenlivet]], the Earl of Huntly sent a messenger to Flanders and the Pope to report their \"happy success\".<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 522-3.</ref>\n\n[[Walter Scott, 1st Lord Scott of Buccleuch|Walter Scott of Buccleuch]] asked [[Anne of Denmark]] to intercede for his life and he was imprisoned and fined.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 524-5, 526.</ref>\n\nHe died in 1606.\n\n==Family==\nJames Scott married Elizabeth Wardlaw, daughter of Andrew Wardlaw of Torrie. Their children included:\n* Barbara Scott, who married David Graham of Fintry.\n* Janet Scott, who married John Boswell of Balmuto.\n* James Scott of Logie, who married Katherine Creick.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, James}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:1606 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Scott_of_Balwearie"}
